tgagcaagggcg...\n    # output: ...atatgagtagattagaagaagaattaagaagaagattaacagaaagcaagggcg...\n    # Let\'s find the insertion point.\n    \n    # The insertion is "tagattagaagaagaattaagaagaagattaacagaa"\n    # It is inserted after "atatgag"\n    # Let\'s find where "atatgag" ends in input_seq.\n    \n    # Wait, the diff showed:\n    # < ...atatgagcaagggcg...\n    # > ...atatgagtagattagaagaagaattaagaagaagattaacagaaagcaagggcg...\n    \n    # Let\'s find the index of "atatgag" in input_seq\n    idx = input_seq.find("atatgag")\n    if idx == -1:\n        # Try finding the part after "atatgag"\n        # The diff showed "caagggcg" in input and "agcaagggcg" in output.\n        # This means "a" was inserted before "caagggcg"? \n        # No, "tagattagaagaagaattaagaagaagattaacagaa" was inserted.\n        # Let\'s look at the diff again.\n        # input:  ...atatgagcaagggcg...\n        # output: ...atatgagtagattagaagaagaattaagaagaagattaacagaaagcaagggcg...\n        # The "caagggcg" in input is now "agcaagggcg" in output? \n        # Let\'s re-read the diff carefully.\n        pass\n\n    # Let\'s use a more robust way to find the difference.\n    # We want to find the primers.\n    # A primer pair for Q5 SDM:\n    # Forward primer: contains the mutation and anneals to the template.\n    # Reverse primer: reverse complement of the forward primer (if it\'s a single mutation)\n    # OR, for Q5, the primers are often designed such that they overlap.\n    # But the task says "the input plasmid will be converted to the output plasmid".\n    # This usually means the primers carry the mutation.\n    # For a circular plasmid, we can use two primers that overlap the mutation site.\n    # The mutation is the insertion of "tagattagaagaagaattaagaagaagattaacagaa".\n    \n    # Let\'s find the exact location of the change.\n    # The change is an insertion.\n    # Let\'s find the longest common prefix and suffix.\n    \n    def get_lcp(s1, s2):\n        i = 0\n        while i < len(s1) and